SIMPLE: piece
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Piece
<hw>Piece</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pece</ets>, F.
<ets>pi⟦egrave⟧ce</ets>, LL. <ets>pecia</ets>, <ets>petia</ets>,
<ets>petium</ets>, probably of Celtic origin; cf. W. <ets>peth</ets> a
thing, a part, portion, a little, Armor. <ets>pez</ets>, Gael. & Ir.
<ets>cuid</ets> part, share. Cf. <er>Petty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A fragment or part of anything separated from the whole, in any
manner, as by cutting, splitting, breaking, or tearing; a part; a
portion; <as>as, a <ex>piece</ex> of sugar; to break in
<ex>pieces</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring it out <qex>piece</qex> by <qex>piece</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xxiv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A definite portion or quantity, as of goods or work;
<as>as, a <ex>piece</ex> of broadcloth; a <ex>piece</ex> of wall
paper.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any one thing conceived of as apart from other
things of the same kind; an individual article; a distinct single effort
of a series; a definite performance</def>; especially: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A literary or artistic composition; <as>as, a <ex>piece</ex> of
poetry, music, or statuary</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A musket, gun,
or cannon; <as>as, a battery of six <ex>pieces</ex>; a following
<ex>piece</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A coin; <as>as, a sixpenny
<ex>piece</ex></as>; -- formerly applied specifically to an English gold
coin worth 22 shillings.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A fact; an item;
<as>as, a <ex>piece</ex> of news; a <ex>piece</ex> of
knowledge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An individual; -- applied to a person as being of a
certain nature or quality; often, but not always, used slightingly or in
contempt.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧If I had not been a <xex>piece</xex> of a
logician before I came to him.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir P.
Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy mother was a <qex>piece</qex> of virtue.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His own spirit is as unsettled a <qex>piece</qex> as there is in
all the world.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- <col><b>a piece of cake</b></col>, <cd>a task easily
accomplished.</cd> -- <col><b>a piece of work</b></col>, <cd>a
disparaging term for a person considered to have an excess of some
undesirable quality; esp. a difficult or eccentric person.</cd> --
<col><b>Piece of ass</b></col> <cd>vulgar term for a woman, considered
as a partner in sexual intercourse.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Chess)</fld> <def>One of the superior men,
distinguished from a pawn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A castle; a fortified building.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Of a piece</b></col>, <cd>of the same sort, as if taken
from the same whole; like; -- sometimes followed by
<xex>with</xex>.</cd> <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>Piece of
eight</b></col>, <cd>the Spanish piaster, formerly divided into eight
reals.</cd> -- <col><b>To give a piece of one's mind to</b></col>,
<cd>to speak plainly, bluntly, or severely to (another).</cd>
<au>Thackeray.</au> -- <col><b>Piece broker</b></col>, <cd>one who buys
shreds and remnants of cloth to sell again.</cd> -- <col><b>Piece
goods</b></col>, <cd>goods usually sold by pieces or fixed portions, as
shirtings, calicoes, sheetings, and the like.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piece</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Piece
<hw>Piece</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pieced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Piecing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make,
enlarge, or repair, by the addition of a piece or pieces; to patch;
<as>as, to <ex>piece</ex> a garment</as>; -- often with
<xex>out</xex>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite; to join; to combine.</def>
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His adversaries . . . <qex>pieced</qex> themselves together in a
joint opposition against him.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piece</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Piece
<hw>Piece</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To unite by a
coalescence of parts; to fit together; to join.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧It
<xex>pieced</xex> better.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pieceless</ent>⟦br⟧
